arXiv:2410.08686v1 Announce Type: new Abstract: In this letter, we perform an almost general analysis of flavor mixing matrices to investigate the discriminative power of CP phases by the next-generation neutrino oscillation experiments. %. As an assumption, we neglect the 1-3 mixing of diagonalization for more hierarchical fermions $u,e$. Thus there are two sources of CP violation in the flavor mixing matrices, the intrinsic CP phase $\delta_{d, 
u}$ in diagonalization of less hierarchical fermions $d, 
u$ and relative phases between two unitary matrices. By eliminating unphysical phases and imposing constraints on the three measured mixing angles, two phases and the 1-2 mixing of more hierarchical fermions $s_{u, e}$ remain free parameters. For sufficiently small 1-2 mixing $s_{e}$ of charged leptons, the Dirac phase $\delta$ is almost identical to the intrinsic phase of neutrinos $\delta_{
u}$. Therefore, future detection of the Dirac phase by the Hyper-Kamiokande experiment indicates the observation of $\delta_{
u}$. On the other hand, if such a CP violation is not observed, an upper limit is placed on a combination of $\delta_{
u}$ and relative phases.

